@voidai・106  Void is shaping up to be the standard liquidity protocol built to enable interoperability for the Bittensor ecosystem

Check out how our design forces the competition to ensure the highest quality liquidity across chains! 

1. Why Miners Need to Rebalance

•SN106 validators score liquidity based on concentration, price alignment, and depth.

•In CLMMs (like Raydium or Uniswap v3), if the market price moves outside a miner’s tick range, their liquidity goes inactive → score drops → emissions earned drop.

•To stay competitive, miners must unstake their NFT, rebalance liquidity closer to mid-price, and restake.

⸻

2. Mechanics of the Cycle
1.Unstake

•Miner withdraws their LP NFT from the SN106 Solana program.

•Once unstaked, they temporarily stop earning emissions.

2.Rebalance

•Miner adjusts their tick range around the new mid-price.

•Trade-offs:

•Tighter ranges = higher score but more frequent rebalancing.

•Wider ranges = less score but less maintenance.

3.Restake

•NFT is re-staked into SN106.

•Validator recognizes new position and begins scoring again.

⸻

3. Short-Term Effects of the Cycle

•Dynamic Liquidity: 

Miners constantly shift their liquidity toward the most active price ranges.

•Fee Volume Rises: 

Even though miners don’t keep fees, every rebalance creates new liquidity around the price, which improves market depth and generates more trades → more fees → treasury growth.

•Competitive Sorting: 

Active, automated miners (using bots) dominate emissions, while passive miners with “set-and-forget” ranges see returns collapse.

⸻

4. Long-Term Effects on Liquidity Quality

1. Permanently Tighter Spreads

Because miners are incentivized to always stay “on price,” liquidity naturally clusters around the mid-price. Over years, this creates very narrow spreads for TAO and alpha tokens on Solana.

2. Depth Where It Matters

Instead of liquidity spread thin across a wide range, emissions incentivize capital where trades actually occur. The result: higher capital efficiency → less slippage → better price discovery.

3. Institutionalization of Mining

Over time, only miners with bots (or a liquidity mining pool) will survive. This professionalizes liquidity and ensures consistently high-quality markets, though it reduces miner diversity.

4. Positive Feedback into Treasury

Every rebalance → tighter spreads → more arbitrage volume → more trading fees → bigger treasury → deeper POL (protocol-owned liquidity). Over time, treasury dominance smooths volatility, making liquidity even more resilient.

5. Subnet-Level Fairness

Since emissions are ratio’d to each subnet’s TAO weight, rebalancing ensures that liquidity depth across subnet pools scales with subnet importance in Bittensor. This ties market quality directly to protocol consensus.

⸻

5. Risks & Mitigations

•Gas/transaction overhead: 

Frequent unstake/rebalance/restake could become costly if Solana fees rise. → Mitigated by bots batching operations and Solana’s low-fee environment.

•Liquidity churn: 

If too many miners rebalance at once, temporary liquidity gaps may appear. → Treasury POL smooths this over by keeping baseline liquidity in pools.

•Centralization of competition:

Over time, only miners with automation can compete effectively. → Liquidity mining pool will democratize access for smaller miners.

⸻

✅ In short: The unstake → rebalance → restake cycle makes SN106’s liquidity self-optimizing. Miners are forced to constantly align capital with market activity, producing tighter spreads, deeper liquidity, and better price discovery. Over the long run, this cycle — combined with treasury POL — ensures TAO and alpha tokens have institution-grade markets across Solana, Ethereum, and Base.

Most liquidity subnets only recycle emissions and fees back to miners, which creates a circular economy that looks attractive in the short term but isn’t sustainable. What is SN106

SN106 is a subnet in the Bittensor ecosystem designed to bring liquidity onto Solana. It bridges Bittensor’s tokens (TAO and alpha tokens) into Solana as wrapped versions (wTAO, wAlpha) and lets miners earn rewards by providing liquidity. 

Instead of simple pools, it uses Raydium’s Concentrated Liquidity Market Maker (CLMM), which is like Uniswap v3: you choose a price range to provide liquidity, not the entire spectrum. 

That liquidity is represented as a position NFT, which you can stake in SN106 to start earning.

⸻

How it works step by step

To get started, you first bridge your Bittensor tokens to Solana, which gives you wrapped versions that work in Solana DeFi.

With those, you go to Raydium and provide liquidity in one of the supported pairs, usually wAlpha/wTAO.

When you choose a price range and deposit liquidity, Raydium mints an NFT representing your position.

You then stake that NFT into SN106’s smart contracts. Once staked, your position is constantly evaluated. 

The system looks at how concentrated your liquidity is (narrow ranges get more weight), how close your range is to the actual trading price (in-range positions earn, out-of-range ones don’t), and how much liquidity you’ve contributed. 

Rewards aren’t just based on your position though — they also scale with how well the entire subnet is performing.

If you’re running the validator software side of things, your job is to collect data from Solana, calculate how good each liquidity position is, and submit weights to Bittensor every scoring interval. That ensures emissions are distributed fairly.

⸻

What performance means

Performance is multi-factor. If you pick a narrow range near the current market price, your liquidity is more useful and you earn more — but it’s also riskier if price moves away. 

Larger amounts of liquidity generally increase your share, but inefficient ranges will drag down performance. 

And, since rewards are partly based on subnet-wide success, your earnings improve if the subnet overall is healthy and in demand.

⸻

Why join SN106

The appeal of SN106 is that it ties Bittensor’s token economy into Solana’s DeFi ecosystem.

As a miner, you get flexibility: you control how tight your ranges are and how much liquidity you provide, balancing risk against potential reward. 

The design ensures that high-quality, in-range positions and active subnet participation are rewarded most.

There isn’t an official full tutorial yet, but you can follow this simple process:
1. **Install Talisman Wallet** (browser extension).
2. **Import your existing Bittensor wallet** by selecting **“Import account from JSON”** or **“Use existing seed phrase.”**
3. Paste your **mnemonic (seed phrase)** or upload your **JSON file** that you originally generated for your subnet wallet.
4. Once imported, your **TAO address** will automatically appear in Talisman — that’s what people mean by *“regen it on Talisman.”*

Essentially, it just means **restoring your Bittensor wallet inside Talisman** using your seed phrase or JSON file.
